{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412790"},"attributes":{"position":18,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13692"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521683"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:35:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:35:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13692"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261074"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":19,"questionsAnswered":7,"marksTotal":19,"marksAttainable":7,"marksAttempted":7,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:39:59+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.14,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"13692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13692"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.11,0.6,0.04,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55904"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6300"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41453"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"3812"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14619"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55904"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of rectal bleeding. He reports occasional tenesmus. He denies any significant weight loss. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Digital rectal examination suggests a fullness in the rectum. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI pelvis","CT chest, abdomen and pelvis","Colonoscopy","CT colonography","Sigmoidoscopy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient presents with rectal bleeding and a mass detected on both digital rectal examination and the CT scan (Image), which is highly suspicious for rectal cancer. The most appropriate next step to confirm the diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E and biopsy. This procedure allows direct visualisation of the entire colon and rectum, and most importantly, enables tissue sampling for histological confirmation of cancer. It may also exclude the rare large rectal polyp which may be suspicious for rectal cancer based on CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is an excellent imaging modality for local staging of rectal cancer, particularly for assessing the depth of tumour invasion and involvement of surrounding structures. However, it does not provide histological confirmation and would typically be performed after the diagnosis is established by biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest, abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for staging colorectal cancer and detecting metastases, but it is not the next step for confirming the diagnosis. This would usually be performed after histological confirmation of cancer to assess for distant spread.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT colonography\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as virtual colonoscopy, can detect colorectal masses but does not allow for biopsy. It is more commonly used as a screening tool or when conventional colonoscopy is incomplete or contraindicated (patients with significant co-morbidities for colonoscopy under sedation).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoidoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially diagnose a rectal mass, but colonoscopy is preferred as it allows examination of the entire colon. This is important because synchronous lesions can occur in up to 5% of colorectal cancer cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while imaging studies play a crucial role in the workup of suspected colorectal cancer, tissue diagnosis remains the cornerstone for confirming the diagnosis. Therefore, colonoscopy with biopsy is the most appropriate next step in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rectal bleeding in an older patient with a mass on imaging is highly suggestive of colorectal cancer.","Colonoscopy with biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosing colorectal cancer, allowing direct visualization and tissue sampling."],"references":["Lotfollahzadeh S, Kashyap S, Tsoris A, et al. Rectal Cancer. In: StatPearls [Online].  [Updated 2023 Jul 4]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK493202/","Lee S, Surabhi VR, Kassam Z, Chang KJ, Kaur H. Imaging of colon and rectal cancer. Current Problems in Cancer. 2023;47(2):100970. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0147027223000235"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41453"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13692"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20653"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21095"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20653"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/sBsarYVHXWOHV1USTIW5cNXmpNiF2c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/sBsarYVHXWOHV1USTIW5cNXmpNiF2c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":800}},{"type":"media","id":"21095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21095"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/yTnLzQk1PIU5F4npjqXdHM8h1uHLdE.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/yTnLzQk1PIU5F4npjqXdHM8h1uHLdE.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":509,"height":295}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41453"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T15:12:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T15:12:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6300"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55904"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"descr